{
  "texts": [
    "In most cases, the weights are fixed to constant values [11], [13], which may be highly suboptimal when the operating conditions change over the prediction window.",
    "On the other hand, ensemble strategies that optimize the weights based on system states, inputs, and outputs [15], [28] are not suited for predictive frameworks, as future measured system states and outputs are not available, and predicted model states and outputs may be inaccurate.To overcome these limitations, we propose a strategy in which the ensemble weights are designed as a function of the input u, and are optimized implicitly along the prediction window, i.e.,λ [i] MD u(h) = 1 T 2 u(h),u [i] n i=1 1 T 2 u(h),u [i],(7)where T 2 u(h), u [i] is the Mahalanobis distancefoot_0, computed according to Definition 2.1, between the current input u(h) and the training inputs of model M [i].",
    "With this approach, the smaller the statistical distance T 2 u(h), u [i] between the input u(h) and the training inputs u [i] of D [i], the larger the weight assigned to the corresponding model output y [i].",
    "Conversely, this combination rule penalizes the predictions of models trained on data that are statistically distant from the current input u(h).",
    "This combination rule offers several advantages over traditional strategies within an MPC framework, as will be shown in Section VI."
  ]
}